2
00:00:06.150 --> 00:00:11.620
In this lecture we're going to take a look
at a pair of challenging English sounds.

3
00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:15.830
They are th as in they, d as in day.

4
00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:22.370
This is a common area of difficulty
in English pronunciation.

5
00:00:22.370 --> 00:00:25.930
Many speakers who mispronounce
these sounds do so

6
00:00:25.930 --> 00:00:28.430
because these sounds don't
occur in their language.

7
00:00:29.710 --> 00:00:34.347
In reality, this [SOUND] sound
involving the speaker's tongue and

8
00:00:34.347 --> 00:00:36.097
top teeth is quite rare.

9
00:00:36.097 --> 00:00:39.900
And many European and
Asian languages lack its equivalent.

10
00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:47.565
For example, in Chinese, Japanese, French,
and German, is an unknown sound so

11
00:00:47.565 --> 00:00:53.986
duh is often used as a substitute because
duh is articulated in a similar way.

12
00:00:53.986 --> 00:00:59.500
Both the th and the duh sounds

13
00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:04.880
are created with the speaker's tongue
being placed behind the top teeth, and

14
00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:10.000
both are voiced, which means we use our
voices to help pronounce the words.

15
00:01:11.020 --> 00:01:13.070
So, this confusion is understandable.

16
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.470
To pronounce the th sound,
you relax your jaw.

17
00:01:19.690 --> 00:01:23.730
Separate your upper and
lower teeth by a few millimeters and

18
00:01:23.730 --> 00:01:27.226
place the tip of your tongue
between your upper and lower teeth.

19
00:01:27.226 --> 00:01:33.420
The th sound is produced by pushing or

20
00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:37.580
letting air flow between your tongue and
teeth while using your vocal cords.

